Grønland - District in Oslo
In lively, multicultural Greenland, there are many shops with food from the Middle East and restaurants that sell kebabs and børek. Informal venues serving curries, laid-back pubs and lively dance clubs can also be found in the area. neighborhood_overview:
From Wikipedia:
Frogner is a borough and an exclusive residential and retail district in the West End of the city of Oslo, Norway. In addition to traditional Frogner, the borough incorporates Bygdøy, Uranienborg and Majorstuen. The borough is named after Frogner Manor, and the famous Frogner Park is now found on the site of the manor. In Oslo, and indeed in Norwegian popular culture, Frogner occupies a similar position as London's Knightsbridge, and has the highest real estate prices in the entire country.

FROGNERPARKEN is the biggest park in the central parts of Oslo. It is a popular recreational area for both its neighbours and people from other parts of Oslo. On a nice summer day, the park is full of people; here you can go for a run, walk the dog, have a picnic or barbecue, play badminton or just do some sunbathing. Frognerparken has Norway's biggest collection of roses; a total of 14,000 plants of 150 different species.

neighborhood_overview:
Frogner is one of Oslo’s most desirable neighborhoods, offering a rich history, beautiful architecture, and a lively social scene. With its upscale shopping, top-rated restaurants, and beautiful parks, Frogner is a great place to live or visit for anyone looking to experience the best of Oslo

Frogner Park and Vigeland Sculpture park:
A gigantic green lung covering almost 500,000 square meters in the middle of the city, the Frogner Park is a great place for a relaxing stroll, or tranquil picnic. If you want to see more than greenery however, visitors have free access to the Vigeland installation – the largest sculpture park in the world created by Gustav Vigeland. With over 200 bronze and granite sculptures depicting the human condition adorning walkways, and the eye-catching Monolith towering on the top plateau, the Frogner Park is a spectacular attraction in both the summer and winter seasons.

name: Beautiful 135 sqm. Fin de siècle apartment
description: Top floor, 135 sqm., 5 rooms, Fin de siecle apartment. Situated as central as possible on Grunerløkka. Public transportation like bus 21 just outside the door and tram 11,12&18 a few meters away. Two main bedrooms and two livingrooms with sofabeds.
neighborhood_overview:
Grünerløkka is a district of the city of Oslo, Norway. Grünerløkka became part of the city of Oslo in 1858. Grünerløkka is a traditional working class district, but from the late 20th century a gentrification process has taken place in the area. Although it is located in the East End, it has a relatively high price level today compared to other East End areas.

It also is considered to be a very hip & revamped neighboorhood. Like this description from Lonely Planet attempts to describe:

"Former factory district turned fashion hub, with laid-back cafes and galleries galore, Grünerløkka is a colourful mix of old and new decor. Independent boutiques and design shops showcase Oslo’s more alternative side, with 19th-century buildings serving as a picturesque backdrop. Recharge with a beer from the local brewery at Grunerløkka Brygghus (https://brygghus.no/) Pop into the Sunday Birkelunden bric-a-brac market to fashionistas on the prowl for vintage items ranging from je
host_about:
Hey! How are you!? 

I'm an art historian born and bred in Oslo with a deep love for the city. Also a frequent traveler having lived among other places for four years in Mexico. 

While in Norway I work at the Institute of Media and Communication at the University of Oslo, but love spending as much time as possible on my sailing boat situated at Hovedøya or in my familys mountain cabin in Rondane. 

See you soon!

name: Cozy apartment in central Oslo
description:
Modern, smart apartment (37 square meters) with comfortable beds. Located at urban and multicultural Grønland. A short walk from most Oslo has to offer.

1 sofabed (140x200 cm) in the living room and one king size bed (180x220 cm) in the bedroom.

The location is urban Grønland, a short walk away from most of what Oslo has to offer. All of public transport stop at Grønland. In other words. From the apartment you can get all over Oslo both easy and fast.
neighborhood_overview:
Allot of attractions and places to eat really close. A short walk away you will find botanical garden and Much Museum. Grønland you will find people with different cultures, this you can see in all the different restaurants and shops.

The apartment is only a 3 min walk from Akerselva. if u want an adventure in nature in the middle of town i recommend walk along Akerselva from Grønland too Nydalen.

If you are looking for a typical Norwegian restaurant you can go to Asylet og Olympen. There is also some cheap dinners close to my apartment where you can get a dinner for 75 kr. I recommend the Somalian restaurant named Jabba and the Pakistani restaurant named Punjab tandoori. They are 20 and 50 meter away from the apartment. The closest big attraction is botanical garden, just a 3-5 min walk away from the apartment.

I work with people that have autism.

Moved to Oslo back in 2015. Love the city, the people and the opportunities the city has to offer.  
On my spare time i like to go out for walks,  be with friends,  make good food,  watch tv series,  fishing, travel, explore, camping and much more. 

Jeg heter Thomas, og er utdannet sosionom. Flyttet til Oslo i oktober, 2015. Jobber på bolig for autister og fullførte nylig master i familieterapi.

My apartment is located at lovely Sagene, surrounded with green parks (not in winter), very close to public transportation, grocery stores, cafés and the city center. name: Mad Architect’s Room by Munch/Opera (free Wi-Fi)
description:
Bright, modern apartment on Sørenga by the Oslo Fjord. Master bedroom for rent with the following shared (with me): bathroom, kitchen, living room, and balcony. Located 5 minutes from Oslo Opera House and the Munch Museum, and 18 minutes from Oslo Central Station. I live alone in the 2nd bedroom.

Wake up with a sea view.

The special square-shaped building was designed by the MAD Architects.

«Life is good at Sørenga»
neighborhood_overview:
When I first came to Sørenga in 2014, I was so surprised by the silence. Yes, Sørenga is close to Oslo Central Station and the city, and yet it was quiet. I could see the city right over there, but basically couldn't hear it.

Then I decided that this is the place I would like to stay. I like peace and quiet, love the sea, need to live near Oslo Central Station so can travel easily elsewhere, as well as have the city close by. So then it became Sørenga for me.

Sørenga consists of only new buildings. Some are more or less built on posts in the water. And there is water between the buildings, and a bridge between the promenade.

We have Sørenga Sjøbad here, an outdoor saltwater pool and a small city beach.

There are built wooden benches one can lie on and just enjoy the view.

Along the promenade there are several great restaurants. My favorite is the Mexican restaurant Coyo. I especially recommend their guacamole.

Sørenga
host_about:
Traveled a lot when I was younger. Now I have the pleasure of meeting people from all over the world in my own apartment.

Trying to make sure that guests who are so kind to book with me have a good stay.

¨Life is good at Sørenga¨

neighborhood_overview:
The apartment is located in city center and is a side street from Torggata.
Torggata is a street in central Oslo known for its many restaurants and bars. In this one fairly short street, reserved for pedestrians and bicycle riders, you can find everything from Starbucks coffee to bubble tea, from kebabs to fine dining, and from trendy fashion to a dedicated cap store. The street that used to be just another street has become a destination in itself, as well a natural link between the trendy Grünerløkka and the vibrant Youngstorget.

Torggata and its side streets offer restaurants like Arakataka, Taco República and Munchies, bars like Tilt and Café Sara, and the brewery/bar Crowbar. Just around the corner you can find large concert venues like Sentrum Scene, Rockefeller and John Dee, making Torggata and its surrounding area a versatile destination that offers something for everyone.

Grünerløkka:
Through Oslo, from north to south, runs the river Akerselva.

Hey, born in Norway, lived in 10 countries, more than 25 years i ve lived outside, but due to Covid i got back to the north, and seems i am still here :-)

The following is about our former space in Guangzhou, China, which we had listed for many years:
Loft345 is an art space in Guangzhou's Haizhu district devoted to exhibitions, a wide range of performances, and affordable booze offered as unpretentiously as possible in a world of nauseating pomposity. Established in 2003 as Park19 and changing its name in 2005, Loft is one of Guangzhou's longest running art spaces. Known for student exhibitions, independent musical artists, and performance pieces ranging from dance to spoken word to the impenetrably strange, Loft attempts to be a place where independently minded artists and people who like to look at art can congregate and enjoy one another's company in peace. Some people describe it as a living room, some a dank hole--we'll leave it up to you to decide.

name: Solrikt hus på øy midt i Oslo
description:
Malmøya is about 4 km from Oslo City Centre. A unique island made up of lush forests, parts of the island are nature reserves. There is a bridge over to the mainland and it takes about 10 minutes by car and 25 min by bike to Oslo city centre.

Outdoor areas and immediate access to hiking trail around the island and small pearls of beaches. Approx. 500m walking distance to bus and land trade.

The house is over three floors and part of a two-person residence located in a quiet and family-friendly residential area.
neighborhood_overview:
There are larger and smaller beaches around the island and there is excellent opportunity for swimming and sunbathing. At Solvikstrand there is also a cosy restaurant. If you have a kayak or A DRINK, take it with you.

There is a short distance to the kindergarten with ballroom swings and slides etc. that can be used as a playground in July and on weekends.

name: Private room in shared central loft, with balcony
description: Private bedroom in shared central loft, only 10 minutes away from central station with public transport, located in the upcoming neighbourhood that is Tøyen. The loft is spacious, with separate bathroom and kitchen and a private balcony! With the metro station only three minutes away, you have excellent access to public transport (all lines stop at Tøyen) to sights and attractions in Oslo. Welcome!
neighborhood_overview:
One of Oslo's fastest up and coming neighbourhoods, with people from all over the world living together in a melting pot which is Tøyen.

Just across the street is Tøyen Torg, with restaurants and cafes, and it is only a short walk down to multicultural Grønland, with amazing food and great places to have a drink. I would be happy to recommend you my favourite local spots based on your desires.

Tøyen is home to several sights, and the Botanical garden, Tøyenparken (where Øya-festivalen takes place, only a few minutes from the apartment), and Tøyenbadet (temporarily closed for rehabilitation) is just a short walk away from the flat.

If you take the metro to the central station, you are just a short walk away from the famous opera house, the new Munch Museum, the National Museum, the Main Library, the city beach and communal swimming area.
host_about:
Half English, half Norwegian, living in Oslo with my partner. I love travelling and meeting new people, and enjoy my role as an Airbnb host.

The last 15 years I have lived in thirteen different homes, in eight different cities, in four different countries. I greatly appreciate people, cultures and languages and pride myself in making sure our home feels welcoming for everyone, no matter who they are.

name: Flott fjordutsikt i elegant sentrumsområde.
description: Welcome to Tjuvholmen, the most exclusive part of Oslo city center! Here you can enjoy the view of the Oslo fjord,  and at the same time be in the immediate vicinity of the beach, bathing jetty, Astrup Fearnly museum, etc. Only 2 minutes away you will find exciting Aker Brygge with all its shops, restaurants, cafes and bakeries. Direct access to the harbour promenade that takes you past Rådhusbrygga (with boat departures to the islands), Akershus Fortress, Opera House, Munch Museum, Bjørvika and all the way out on Sørenga.
neighborhood_overview:
The apartment is located in Tjuvholmen, a stylish area of Oslo. From the living room window you look straight down to the Astrup Fearnly museum and gallery Pushwagner. Outside the apartment is also Oslo's observation tower; Peeping. A few meters away are several piers, beach and green area open to the public.
Nearest neighboring area is Aker pier with all its restaurants, cafes, galleries, shops. and the new National Museum. At the end of Aker brygge you will find Rådhusplassen with boat departures to the islands in the Oslo Fjord and to Nesodden. The harbour promenade along the fjord goes via Tjuvholmen and Aker Brygge, past Akershus fortress and all the way to Barcode/Bjørvika and Sørenga. It is only 10 minutes walk to the apartment from Nationaltheatret station (trains and subways), and only 4 minutes walk to the nearest bus stop.

The revitalized port district Bjørvika is known for its striking contemporary architecture!
Bjørvika is a treasure trove ready to be discovered. The white Opera house, the narrow buildings of the Barcode ensemble and the quirky angles of Akrobaten pedestrian bridge have become popular photography spots for locals and visitors. In Barcode, you can find high-end shops, art galleries and restaurant.

Across the street and towards the fjord, lies the new MUNCH and the Oslobukta neighbourhood: A completely new borough with a wide variety of restaurants, architectural sights, a large swimming pier and a water fountain that doubles as a playground.

If you walk onwards across the pontoon bridge from the Opera house, you get to Sørenga, where you can relax in a floating sauna, enjoy urban beach life and go kayaking. name: Double Room in Central Oslo
description: This room has everything you need to live, work and play. Get the practical things like fast WiFi, 24/7 support, and regular professional cleaning. Plus fun stuff like a smart TV, instant camera and yoga mat.
neighborhood_overview: It really doesn’t get more central in Oslo than the Kvadraturen neighbourhood where Bob W Sentralen is located. Kvadraturen gets its name from the neat, quadrant-like streets running through it. In 1624, after a fire levelled the town, Danish-Norwegian King Christian IV ordered the town to be built anew in its present location following the ideals of Rennaissance architecture. Today, you can enjoy the area’s historic charm and modern conveniences all wrapped into one.
host_about:
Bob is the mythical globetrotter who calls nowhere home but is at ease anywhere. After travelling around the world from Chicago to Kathmandu and everywhere in between, Bob has developed refined taste when it comes to accommodation. His holy grail are places that blend the consistent quality of a hotel with the authentic flair and affordability of a host’s home. The problem is that these types of places are almost impossible to find. That’s why he decided to create his own category of exceptionally cool short-stay accommodation that combine the best of both worlds. 

When you sleep with Bob, you always know what to expect: an awesome location in a handpicked neighbourhood, interiors created by local designers, and a commitment to sustainability. Although Bob is usually away trekking up a glacier or hitchhiking across a continent, his team of professional hospitality superheros is here for you day and night to make sure you have a 5-star stay. Welcome to Bob’s world!

name: Spacious Double Room, located in Kvadraturen, Oslo
description: This room has everything you need to live, work and play. Get the practical things like fast WiFi, 24/7 support, and regular professional cleaning. Plus fun stuff like a smart TV, instant camera and yoga mat.
neighborhood_overview: It really doesn’t get more central in Oslo than the Kvadraturen neighbourhood where Bob W Sentralen is located. Kvadraturen gets its name from the neat, quadrant-like streets running through it. In 1624, after a fire levelled the town, Danish-Norwegian King Christian IV ordered the town to be built anew in its present location following the ideals of Rennaissance architecture. Today, you can enjoy the area’s historic charm and modern conveniences all wrapped into one.
host_about:
Bob is the mythical globetrotter who calls nowhere home but is at ease anywhere. After travelling around the world from Chicago to Kathmandu and everywhere in between, Bob has developed refined taste when it comes to accommodation. His holy grail are places that blend the consistent quality of a hotel with the authentic flair and affordability of a host’s home. The problem is that these types of places are almost impossible to find. That’s why he decided to create his own category of exceptionally cool short-stay accommodation that combine the best of both worlds. 

When you sleep with Bob, you always know what to expect: an awesome location in a handpicked neighbourhood, interiors created by local designers, and a commitment to sustainability. Although Bob is usually away trekking up a glacier or hitchhiking across a continent, his team of professional hospitality superheros is here for you day and night to make sure you have a 5-star stay. Welcome to Bob’s world!

description: Discover the modern and stylish apartment in the trendy Bjørvika area of Oslo, surrounded by stunning architecture, top-rated restaurants, and easy access to popular attractions. Walk to the Opera, Munch Museum, Deichman Library, Medieval Park, and enjoy a variety of restaurants and shopping options on Karl Johan Street. Sauna visit, urban beach life, and kayaking. On the opposite side of the bay, the art village SALT offers a rich cultural program, along with panoramic views!
neighborhood_overview:
The Bjørvika area, is highly sought-after due to its stunning architecture, excellent restaurants, and convenient location. Just steps away from the apartment, you'll find several popular attractions, including the Oslo Opera House, Munch Museum, Deichman Library, and Central Station among others. Take a stroll up to the old town to see the Royal Castle and Parliament, and enjoy a variety of restaurants and shopping options.

If you take a walk to Sørenga, you'll find opportunities for sauna visits, urban beach life, and kayaking. On the opposite side of the bay, the art village SALT offers a rich cultural program, along with wood-fired saunas! As you continue along the harbor promenade past SALT, you can take a detour to Akershus Fortress and Castle, which has guarded the city since the 14th century.

name: Old World glamour on the park!
description:
Welcome to our bright, beautifully detailed home. We have restored (and continue to nurture!) this spacious park-front apartment in an 1896 neoclassical building. Pine floors, 28 windows, french doors, and 127 years of history. Borrow our hammock for a day in St. Hanshaugen park: grab a beer at the open air resto, grill some gourmet sausages from Gutta På Haugen, and enjoy the Oslo fjord view. :)
Situated in a neighborhood of cafes, art galleries, and boutiques, we’re also 5 mins from downtown.
neighborhood_overview: This is the best neighborhood in Oslo! Not as uptight as Frogner, but a little more polished than Grunerlokka. It’s safe, eclectic, full of architect and design studios, has some wonderful cafes, and so many options for eating and drinks. We rarely go downtown for date night because it’s all here! Plus, the park is extremely family friendly with FOUR playgrounds, a plethora of cute dogs, and lots of green space. I cannot emphasize the quality of this neighborhood enough. Am I bragging? Yes I am.
host_about: I'm a therapist and media professional, and travel often with my two kids (ages 7 and 5) and my husband, a physicist. We live in Oslo! I love nothing more than meeting new people, except maybe seeing new art. My favorite travel destination: Galle. It's a city built around a 16th Century Dutch fort on the South Western coast of Sri Lanka. It's full of all this incredible crumbling art deco architecture. I lost my MIND with how beautiful it was when I went there. I had stupidly left my camera at my friend's house, so I purchased a disposable camera and took a lot of photos that came out terrible. C'est la vie.

name: Lun og innbydende hybel i kjeller
description:
Welcoming and peaceful accommodation, centrally located. This dorm sits in a quiet street, in a small residential area just a stone's throw away from Carl Berner, which is a public hub.
The apartment is located in the basement of a 100 year old Swiss villa, it has a private entrance and private dining area adjacent to this one.
The apartment has its own kitchen with everything needed, bathroom w shower and a bedroom with double bed and office space. The living room has a "cuddle nook" for any accommodation for 1 big or 2 small, extra.
neighborhood_overview: This is a quiet little residential area just a 4 min walk from Carl Berner which is the hub for public transport in Oslo. It is also not far to walk to the botanical garden, Greenland, the match, Sagene or Grünerløkka, if you want to hike. It is 3 min walk to the grocery store, pharmacy, flower shop and wine monopoly. 10 min to the botanical garden, 7 min to Tøyen park, and 15 min to Grünerløkka. City bikes are easily accessible at Carl Berner, if it is desired to experience Oslo by bike. This apartment is centrally located to reach all of the city's sights, at the same time as secluded and located in a very quiet and cozy area.
host_about: Jeg heter Katinka og er gift med Andreas, vi har tre barn og huset vi bor i har mine oldeforeldre bygget, og vi prøver som best vi kan å ta vare på det. Vi har skiftet kledning, skiftet vinduer, drenert og skiftet tak de siste årene, og det meste gjør vi selv. Vi ønsker å ta vare på så mye som mulig av de gamle materialene, derfor gjenbruker vi så mye som vi kan. Vi elsker huset, men det er for stort for oss, derfor leier vi ut en liten del:)

name: Appartement with fireplace and a view
description:
Welcome to my sunny home. This place is quiet, no intrusion, warm colors and great possibility to relax, only ten minutes away with bus from the city centre.

The apartment faces the Etterstad colony garden and has a view over the city. In June 2023, the balcony will be upgraded and refurbished, so you can watch the sun until it sets.
neighborhood_overview:
Vålerenga is calm, quiet and beautiful, and mainly consists of small wooden houses and nice streets. 100 meters away is Vålerenga church, with a lovely park outside. 500 meters away is Kruttverket, a kind of cultural center with sauna, concerts, small flea market and cafe. Take a stroll along the alna river to Svartdalsparken and experience primeval forest, or walk 10 minutes to Kampen og Tøyen, where you will find cozy cafes and pubs.

Bus 37 is nearby and takes you to the center in ten minutes and runs all night, otherwise you can walk for 10 minutes and take the subway from Ensjø.

name: 18th Flr Gem Oslo Views & Luxury
description:
Experience Oslo's 18th-Floor Oasis in the Heart of the City

Welcome to your urban sanctuary in Oslo. Nestled on the 18th floor of a sleek and modern building, this stunning 50sqm apartment is designed to accommodate up to four guests. Whether you're a tourist, a business traveler, a couple on a date night, or a small family, this exquisite space promises a memorable stay. The city's wonders which can be reachd by foot from this chic urban apartment await you just beyond your window.
neighborhood_overview:
Nestled in the heart of Oslo, this apartment is a mere 5-minute stroll from Oslo S, the central transportation hub. Immerse yourself in the culinary delights of Oslo with a plethora of high-quality restaurants just a stone's throw away. Explore the cultural scene with nearby attractions like the iconic Oslo Opera House, the Munch Museum, and the bustling Karl Johans gate shopping street. Convenient access to buses, trains, and the subway makes exploring Oslo a breeze, with the "Oslo City" shopping mall only a 10-minute walk away.

Savor the flavors of Oslo at renowned eateries like "Våghals" (2 minutes on foot), "Oslo Streetfood" (right next door), Noodee Barcode, and Maaemo. Relish your morning coffee at Joe & The Juice across the street or treat yourself to gelato at Paradis Gelateria (5-minute walk).
host_about:
Hello! I’m Fredrik

A joyful Swiss-Norwegian in Oslo, passionate about both hosting and exploring the world via Airbnb, which has led to some of my life's best experiences. 

My home reflects my love for diverse cultures, aiming to offer guests unique and authentic adventures. 

As a seasoned traveler, I understand the value of a memorable stay. Eager to ensure your trip is exceptional. 

Let’s create lasting memories together! 

- Fredrik

neighborhood_overview:
Grünerløkka - a native's guide to Oslo's soul!

Grünerløkka, once a worn working-class neighborhood, is now home to the creative masses and hip urbanites. The best way to get to know Grünerløkka is by strolling along the river, a favorite activity among locals but still relatively unknown to tourists.

Furthermore, at the Vulkan area, you'll find Mathallen, Oslo's largest food market, and Dansens Hus in former factory premises. This area is great for lunch and cultural experiences. Blå hosts a Sunday market and intimate concerts, while SYNG, Oslo's largest karaoke bar, is nearby. Ankerbrua, known as the 'Fairytale Bridge,' features sculptures from Norwegian folklore and is a wonderful place to explore Grünerløkka's streets.

Grünerløkka is characterized by its mix of old and new, trendy and traditional, giving the area a unique atmosphere. You can explore the treasures found here or simply wander and savor Grünerløkka's distinctive vibe. Vintage and second

Alexander Kielland's place is located in the middle between Grünerløkka and St. Hanshaugen. The property is located in an attractive area, close to Akerselva.

neighborhood_overview:
Castle (Royal Castle): Located nearby, where you can visit the Castle and see the changing of the guard that takes place daily in summer.

Slottsparken: This is the royal park around the Castle, where you can enjoy a leisurely stroll or a picnic.

Karl Johan street: This is Oslo's main street, known for shops, restaurants and a lively atmosphere. You can explore the street and shop

The National Gallery: If you're interested in art, the National Gallery houses an impressive collection of Norwegian and international works.

Stortinget: You can take a guided tour of the Norwegian Parliament building to learn about the country's political system and history.

Aker Brygge: A lively harbor area with lots of restaurants, bars, and stores. A great place to relax, eat, or stroll along the harbor.

Oslo Cathedral: Located in the heart of Oslo, this historic cathedral is worth a visit for its architecture and cultural significance.

neighborhood_overview:
A leafy neighbourhood to the west of Oslo city centre that's popular with expats.

Best known for its high-end shopping, swish restaurants, and luxury apartment blocks, Frogner is one of the most desirable areas to live in Oslo for foreigners. And Norwegians too, for that matter!

The area is well-connected to the city centre by tram and bus for the rainy days, but when the sun shines it's a pleasant walk or cycle ride via Solli plass

The borough of Frogner includes the area known as Frogner but also much of the rest of western Oslo such as Bygdøy, Uranienborg and Majorstuen.

The streets Bygdøy allé and Frognerveien are considered the heart of Frogner itself by most locals. On Frognerveien in particular, you'll find exclusive stores selling the very latest in furniture and interiors side-by-side with antique shops, cafes and restaurants.

neighborhood_overview:
A leafy neighbourhood to the west of Oslo city centre that's popular with expats.

Best known for its high-end shopping, swish restaurants, and luxury apartment blocks, St Hanshaugen is one of the most desirable areas to live in Oslo for foreigners. And Norwegians too, for that matter!

The area is well-connected to the city centre by tram and bus for the rainy days, but when the sun shines it's a pleasant walk or cycle ride via Bislett area.

The borough of St Hanshaugen includes the area known as St Hanshaugen park but also much of the rest of western Oslo such as Bislett, Uranienborg and Majorstuen.

The streets Thereses gate and Pillestedet are considered the heart of Bislett itself by most locals. On Frognerveien in particular, you'll find exclusive stores selling the very latest in furniture and interiors side-by-side with antique shops, cafes and restaurants.

neighborhood_overview: Gamlebyen, Oslo's historic Old Town, is a charming area known for its well-preserved architecture and cobbled streets, offering a unique glimpse into the city's medieval past. This district, nestled in the city's eastern part, is rich in history, featuring the Medieval Park with ruins of ancient churches. Today, Gamlebyen is a vibrant neighborhood, boasting art galleries, cozy cafes, and boutique shops. It's an ideal spot for those looking to explore Oslo's history while enjoying the local culture and quaint atmosphere. Perfect for visitors seeking an authentic and serene experience close to the city's heart.

name: Oslo Downtown Apt. Extremely Central & Low-Priced!
description: More central and easy, you can't get it! In this place, your family will stay close to everything one might need and will see in Oslo. An exciting place to stay with bustling life. The location is very central. Bus, Train, Fly-Train, Metro is Max 100-200 meters away. The place is known for its diverse cultures, restaurants, nightlife venues, vegetable shops, cafes, and sights. Spektrum Arena, is 100m away. I myself have lived on several edges of Oslo, but I like 100 % best right here. Welcome!
neighborhood_overview: The neighborhood is known as Norway's most varied and exciting neighborhood. Here you have the Akers river that runs through Oslo, the sea on the other side of the train station, bike/walk/run trails - restaurants from many different countries. Norwegian, Indian, Greek, Italian, Turkish, etc. Everything from Starbucks to street food parks and historic landmarks. Garage can also be found here. Shops are generally open late and it is lively and easy to live here.

Nærmeste nabo er Oslo Plaza Hotel og Oslo Spektrum Arena. Her er det mye spennende å foreta seg. Jeg har bodd på flere kanter av Oslo, men trives absolutt best «akkurat her». Kom! Du/dere vil elske dette nabolaget :) Mvh. E John

description:
A lovely corner apartment located very centrally in Tøyen with walking distance to the city center, close to the subway with all lines, several bus connections and Oslo central station

Nearby are Tøyenparken, Botanical Garden, Kampen fountain, Jordal sports park and Botsparken.
There are many good restaurants at Tøyen Torg and Grønland.

The apartment is fully furnished, with good kitchen facilities, and includes coffee and tea.

We want to make sure our guests are comfortable!
neighborhood_overview:
It is an urban and stylish neighborhood with nice architecture and great parks nearby. The Botanical Garden just nearby is among the nicest in all of Oslo.

There is excellent access to restaurants in many price ranges both at Tøyen Torg, on the rest of Tøyen and in Grønland

For the family, there are several nice playgrounds in the area: Sørli Playground 2 blocks north-west, Kirsebærlunden playground at Tøyen subway and Snippenparken 7 minutes north-west at the Botanical Garden.

On hot days it is very nice to enjoy the sun in the parks nearby, especially Tøyenparken and the parks in the Botanical Garden.

description:

host_about:
I am a psychologist that is currently taking a PhD in clinical psychology. My life consists of working, spending time with family and friends, going to the theatre, cinema, concerts, trying to keep up with politics and what's happening in the world. 

Love to read, play volleyball also enjoy other sports. 

A perfect vacation in my opinion involves a lot of walking, exploring new places, getting to know the local people and culture, searching trough the area to find the best food, relaxing in a park with cheese, wine and a good book. A good vacation is the balance between relaxing /enjoying and exploring/getting new impulses. If you are planning a stay in Oslo, I am glad to help you to get the most out of your stay, whether you just want to stroll around eat and drink good, or want to get to know the quirks of the city.

I have travelled a lot the previous years (road-trip in USA, Marocco, Israel, Germany, England, France and Italy to mention a few). I've always stayed at hotels/hostels, and I think airbnb is a good alternative to the mundane hotel/hostel life. To get to stay in another person's home is a privilege. As a guest I think I would be seen as tidy, responsible, easy to co-operate with and in general a nice person. I have experience with people renting a room in my own flat, and know how important it is to have people you can trust and like. As a host, I take pride in offering the same things I would want when I travel: a nice and clean place to retreat from the city noice, where you can relax and be comfortable.
